    {
      "type": "grammar",
      "title": "Number Agreement Basics",
      "explanation": "In Serbian, the noun following a number changes form depending on the number. After 'jedan' (1), the noun stays in its basic singular form. After 'dva' (2), 'tri' (3), and 'četiri' (4), nouns take a special plural form (roughly equivalent to the genitive singular for masculine/neuter). After numbers 5 and above, nouns take the genitive plural form. For example: 'jedan dinar' (one dinar), 'dva dinara' (two dinars), 'pet dinara' (five dinars). The number 'dva' also changes based on gender: 'dva' for masculine/neuter and 'dve' (две) for feminine nouns.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "One dinar",
          "serbian_cyrillic": "Један динар",
          "serbian_latin": "Jedan dinar"
        },
        {
          "english": "Two dinars",
          "serbian_cyrillic": "Два динара",
          "serbian_latin": "Dva dinara"
        },
        {
          "english": "Five dinars",
          "serbian_cyrillic": "Пет динара",
          "serbian_latin": "Pet dinara"
        },
        {
          "english": "Two women",
          "serbian_cyrillic": "Две жене",
          "serbian_latin": "Dve žene"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "cultural_note",
      "title": "Counting on Fingers the Serbian Way",
      "content": "Serbians count on their fingers differently than many Western Europeans and Americans. They start counting with the thumb as number one, then add the index finger for two, the middle finger for three, and so on. This means that holding up your index finger alone does not signify 'one' — it would be confusing! If you hold up your thumb, that clearly means 'one' in Serbia and most of the Balkans. This is a small but useful detail when ordering at a busy cafe or market where it might be too noisy to speak. The Serbian currency is the dinar (динар), and you will use numbers constantly when shopping, paying for transport, or tipping."
    }
